{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Sh1wa6H7wQmCRho1B5iQFk","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me design the handlers component.\n\n**Summary of what I know:**\n\n- Module: `github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/acceptance-spec/sandbox/regressions/user-service`\n- Store package: `internal/userservice/store`\n- Store struct has methods: `Create(name, email string) User`, `Get(id string) (User, bool)`, `Update(id, name, email string) (User, bool)`, `Delete(id string) bool`\n- User struct: `ID string`, `Name string`, `Email string`\n\n\n- Handlers will live in `/Users/david/Go/src/github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/acceptance-spec/sandbox/regressions/user-service/output/internal/userservice/handlers`\n\nNow I'm mapping out the API endpoints: POST /users creates a new user and returns 201 with the user object, GET /users/{id} retrieves a user or returns 404, and PUT /users/{id} updates an existing user. I need to handle JSON validation and return appropriate error codes.\n\nFor the implementation, I'm thinking about how to structure the handlers package with a Store interface that abstracts away the concrete store implementation. The interface should expose Create, Get, Update, and Delete methods that match what the handlers need, which keeps the handlers decoupled from the actual storage layer. a local User type or just use the store.User type. Actually, since the store is in the same module, I can just import the store package and use `store.User`. But defining a local interface with methods that return `store.User` would still require importing store. \n\n   Alternatively, I could define a local `User` struct in the handlers package and have the interface return that. But that creates unnecessary complexity with type conversion.\n\n   The cleanest approach: define a `Store` interface in the handlers package that uses the `store.User` type from the store package. This way, the `*store.Store` satisfies the interface automatically.\n\n   Actually, even cleaner: just define the interface in terms of what we need — but we need to return a User type. Since the store.User is already defined, we import it.\n\n   Wait — actually, the simplest and most idiomatic Go approach here is:\n   - Import the store package in handlers\n   - Define a `Store` interface that matches the concrete store's methods and returns `store.User`\n\n   This is fine for an internal service. No need to over-engineer. For the handler function, I'll use `New(s Store) http.Handler` to register routes on a `net/http.ServeMux` and return it. Go 1.22+ pattern matching is available since go.mod specifies 1.25.5, so I can use the enhanced routing syntax for `GET /users/{id}`, `PUT /users/{id}`, `DELETE /users/{id}`, and `POST /users`. I'll handle JSON encoding and decoding with the standard library, use proper JSON tags for the response fields, return an empty JSON object for 404s, and use 204 for successful deletions.\n\n   For the files, I need `handlers.go` with the main handler and all route handlers, plus `handlers_test.go` for tests. I'll define internal request and response structs with the appropriate JSON tags, extract the ID from the URL path using `r.PathValue(\"id\")` with the enhanced ServeMux, and handle errors appropriately — malformed JSON gets a 400, missing resources get a 404 with an empty object, and successful operations return the right 2xx status.\n\nI need to organize the implementation into two files and define the request/response types with proper JSON tags, extract path parameters using the enhanced routing, and handle the error cases correctly.\n\nNow I'm writing the README and then finalizing the response with all the acceptance criteria.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1209,"cache_read_input_tokens":21249,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_in